		<td><b>Re: How to make a FC to NES cartridge converter?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Want to say that you could get a Nintendo-made FC to NES cartridge converter too...  found two so far... walk into a GameStop type store and compare all the NES Gyromite and Stack-Up cartridges... the heavyer ones have Nintendo-made FC to NES cartridge converters... they were created to put a Stack-Up or Gyromite FC cartrige in an nes cause Nintendo had excess amount of FC Gyromite and Stack-Up cartridges.  And these two games were created at the beginning of the nes-era and so can be opened up with a tiny flat-head screwdriver.  Then unscrew the two screws inside... and then pull out and discard the Gyromite or Stack-Up FC cartridge... and pull apart any FC cartridge you could find on ebay and insert it into the converter... heat up the end of a large flat-head screwdriver until it gets a little red, like with a candle, and then carefully slide the center screwhole of the NES cartridge over and then out and away from the inside of the lower NES cartridge case.  Try to do this before heating your screwdriver and remember that you wont be able to touch the end when it's hot.   Give the plastic some time to dry; then rescrew the converter back into the nes cartridge and rescrew the cartridge back together again; don't rescrew the middle screw.  And then play it! <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />  It is important to clean the two cartridge parts with some Isopropyl Alcohol and some cue-tips.  Before that you could  also clean a lot of the dark marks away with an ink eraser.  I found my Gyromite cartridge converter about two years ago... so I guess all of this is still possible.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


